				<div itemprop="commentText" class='post entry-content '>
					<!--cached-Mon, 21 Jul 2014 05:00:17 +0000-->I will add some things that are not specific to osCommerce, but are very good to have to prevent attacks (in addition to all that was said):<br />
<br />
<br />
1-Use strong passwords for the admin interface and FTP/SFTP/SSH. Sound obvious, but we see so many sites hacked through brute force attacks that it is not even funny.<br />
<br />
<br />
2-If you have additional sites in the same FTP account (on shared hosts), make sure all of them are updated and secure too. Otherwise an attack in one of them can spread to the other sites...<br />
<br />
<br />
3-If you are on a dedicated server (or VPS), monitor your server closely. A good tool is the open source OSSEC (free): <a href='http://www.ossec.net' class='bbc_url' title='External link' rel='nofollow external'>http://www.ossec.net</a> . It will check all your logs, files, etc for attacks and block them.<br />
<br />
<br />
4-Daily offsite backups. If your site is compromised or you have a hosting error (or even by mistake), make sure you can easily recover your files and database. There are some many services that offer that (and they are cheap). Examples: <a href='http://gudado.com' class='bbc_url' title='External link' rel='nofollow external'>http://gudado.com</a> , site-vault.com, etc.<br />
<br />
<br />
5-Check your site for malware/spam/etc. I am a bit biased on this, but I recommend checking your site for security issues. The earlier your know that something is happening, the earlier you can respond and fix things. A free checker: <a href='http://sitecheck.sucuri.net' class='bbc_url' title='External link' rel='nofollow external'>http://sitecheck.sucuri.net</a><br />
<br />
<br />
Thanks,
					
					<br />
					
				</div>
				
				
